The '''Grand Musée du Parfum''' was a Paris perfumery museum that operated from December 22, 2016 to July 6, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://wwd.com/beauty-industry-news/beauty-features/le-grand-musee-du-parfum-shutters-in-paris-1202751003/|title=Le Grand Musée du Parfum Shutters in Paris|last=Weil|first=Jennifer|date=2018-07-06|work=WWD|access-date=2018-07-07|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{cite news |last1=Artaud |first1=Ophélie |title=Fermeture du Grand Musée du Parfum à Paris |url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/sortir-paris/2018/07/06/30004-20180706ARTFIG00246-fermeture-du-grand-musee-du-parfum-a-paris.php |accessdate=7 July 2018 |work=Figaro |date=6 July 2018 |language=fr-FR}}</ref> It was founded by entrepreneur Guillaume de Maussion<ref>{{cite news |last1=Meltzer |first1=Hannah |title=A first look inside Le Grand Musée de Parfum, a museum of scent in Paris |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/france/paris/articles/le-grand-musee-du-parfum--an-immersive-multi-sensory-perfume-jou/ |accessdate=7 July 2018 |work=The Telegraph |date=December 22, 2016}}</ref> and overseen by industry experts including [[Jean-Claude Ellena]], then the in-house perfumer at Hermes; [[Mathilde Laurent]], house perfumer at [[Cartier (jeweler)|Cartier]]; and [[Sylvaine Delacourte]], director of fragrance for [[Guerlain]].<ref name=":1">{{cite news |last1=Nicklin |first1=Mary Winston |title=Paris's New Perfume Museum Smells Amazing (Obviously) |url=https://www.cntraveler.com/story/a-sneak-peek-at-pariss-new-grand-musee-du-parfum |accessdate=7 July 2018 |work=Condé Nast Traveler |date=November 28, 2016 |language=en}}</ref> The museum, developed over two years<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/life/2016/12/29/visiting-the-luxurious-but-not-elitist-le-grand-musee-du-parfum-in-paris.html|title=Visiting the luxurious but not elitist Le Grand Musee du Parfum in Paris|last=Helmi|first=Kunang|date=December 29, 2016|work=The Jakarta Post|access-date=2018-07-08|language=en}}</ref> for $7 million,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.harpersbazaar.com/culture/travel-dining/news/a20990/perfume-museum-paris/|title=This Extraordinary New Museum Doesn't Actually Have Any Art|last=Sayej|first=Nadja|date=2017-04-10|work=Harper's Bazaar|access-date=2018-07-07|language=en-US}}</ref> was Iocated in the ''[[hôtel particulier]]'' (townhouse mansion) at 73, [[rue du Faubourg Saint-Honoré]],<ref name=":0" /> once the residence of the [[Louis Roederer|Roederer champagne family]] and later the location of fashion house [[Christian Lacroix]].<ref name=":1" /> Entry cost between 5 and 14.50 Euro.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.europe1.fr/culture/le-grand-musee-du-parfum-a-paris-ferme-au-bout-dun-an-et-demi-3703514|title=Le Grand Musée du parfum à Paris ferme au bout d'un an et demi|last=|first=|date=July 6, 2018|work=Europe 1|access-date=2018-07-08|language=fr-FR}}</ref> Exhibits included a recreation of the laboratory of French perfume house [[Houbigant Parfum|Houbigant]] (founded in 1775 at 19, rue du Faubourg-Saint-Honoré), using items on loan from the [[Musée Carnavalet]] (the museum of the history of Paris).<ref name=":1" /> It also had a "garden of scent" with white sculptures that each released different scents.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/the-newly-opened-le-grand-mus%C3%A9e-du-parfum-in-paris-tells-the-story-of-fragrance-1.37341|title=The newly opened Le Grand Musée du Parfum in Paris tells the story of fragrance|last=Fearon|first=Francesca|date=January 8, 2017|work=The National|access-date=2018-07-08|language=en}}</ref>

