{{Orphan|date=September 2018}}
The '''Improvised Explosive Device Countermeasure Equipment (ICE)''' is a vehicle-mounted electronics-based jamming system that uses low-power [[radio frequency]] energy to thwart enemy [[Improvised explosive device|improvised explosive devices (IEDs)]]. The radio frequency energy it emits blocks the signals broadcast by radio-controlled detonators, such as cell phones and cordless telephones, that would otherwise trigger the hidden IED to explode.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wilson|first=Clay|date=November 21, 2007|title=Improvised Explosive Devices (IEDs) in Iraq and Afghanistan: Effects and Countermeasures|url=http://www.dtic.mil/docs/citations/ADA475029|journal=CRS Report for Congress|language=en|volume=|pages=|via=Defense Technical Information Center}}</ref> ICE was developed by the [[United States Army Research Laboratory|Army Research Laboratory (ARL)]] at [[White Sands Missile Range]] and the Physical Science Laboratory (PSL) at [[New Mexico State University]] in 2004 to counter the rising IED threat in Iraq. Due to the urgent demand for counter-IED equipment, ICE was designed and built within three weeks and was provided to troops in less than six months after the project started.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.defenseindustrydaily.com/field-report-putting-the-ice-on-ieds-0916/|title=Field Report: Putting the ICE on IEDs|last=|first=|date=July 26, 2005|work=Defense Industry Daily|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://researchmag.nmsu.edu/2006/03/02/putting-the-ice-on-ieds/|title=Putting the ICE on IEDs|last=Hill|first=Karl|date=March 2, 2006|work=New Mexico State University Research and Resources|access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref>
ICE was designed to be adaptable to future adjustments in order to keep up with changing IED technology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.defense-aerospace.com/article-view/release/60428/new-us-army-device-counters-ieds-(jul-22).html|title=New Device Counters Terrorism, Keeps Troops Alive|last=|first=|date=July 21, 2005|website=www.defense-aerospace.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref> In addition, it was simple enough for soldiers to repair it at the unit level. Researchers later developed a portable version of ICE called Dismounted IED Countermeasures Equipment (DICE), which allowed soldiers to carry the jamming system in a backpack.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://defensesystems.com/articles/2008/11/army-puts-fcs-network-through-paces-in-demo.aspx|title=Army Puts FCS Network Through Paces in Demo|last=Carr|first=David|date=November 17, 2008|work=Defense Systems|access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref>
ICE proved to be largely successful against the IED threat and several thousand ICE systems were deployed to U.S. military personnel. In 2005, it was recognized as one of the U.S. Army’s "Top Ten Greatest Inventions of 2004," and the award was shared between those who spearheaded the project, ARL’s Shane Cunico, PSL’s Sam Mares, and Maj. Raymond Pickering.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.spacewar.com/reports/NMSU_Physical_Science_Laboratory_Helps_Put_The_ICE_On_Explosives_In_Iraq.html|title=NMSU Physical Science Laboratory Helps Put The ICE On Explosives In Iraq|last=|first=|date=September 15, 2005|website=www.spacewar.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-11}}</ref>
